Considering first [latex]R(s)[/latex] only, then [latex]Y(s)[/latex] is [latex]Y_{1}(s)[/latex] [latex]
\begin{aligned}
 \frac{Y_{1}(s)}{R(s)}&=\frac{\frac{G(s)}{1+G(s) H(s)}}{1+\frac{G(s)}{1+G(s) H(s)}} \\
 \frac{Y_{1}(s)}{R(s)}&=\frac{G(s)}{1+G(s) H(s)+G(s)} \\
 Y_{1}(s)&=\left[\frac{G(s)}{1+G(s)+G(s) H(s)}\right] R(s) \\
 G_{1}(s)&=\frac{G(s)}{1+G(s)+G(s) H(s)}
\end{aligned}
[/latex] Now considering [latex]D(s)[/latex] only, then [latex]Y(s)[/latex] is [latex]Y_{2}(s)[/latex] [latex]
\begin{aligned}
\frac{Y_{2}(s)}{D(s)} & =\frac{G(s)}{1+G(s)[1+H(s)]} \\
Y_{2}(s) & =\left[\frac{G(s)}{1+G(s)+G(s) H(s)}\right] D(s) \\
G_{2}(s) & =\frac{G(s)}{1+G(s)+G(s) H(s)}
\end{aligned}
[/latex] Hence, [latex]G_{1}(s)[/latex] and [latex]G_{2}(s)[/latex] both are equal.

